      "content": "# Python Programming Fundamentals\n\nBy definition, Python is a high-level, general-purpose programming language.. Put simply, Python is consistently ranked among the top programming languages..\n\n## Notable Features\n\n- Python Programming Language.\n- Python supports multiple programming paradigms including object-oriented\n- Python supports procedural\n- Python supports functional programming\n- Python has a comprehensive standard library.\n- Python uses dynamic typing and garbage collection.\n- Python Official Documentation.\n- Python has several built-in data types including integers\n- Python has floating-point numbers\n- Python has strings\n- Python has lists\n- Python has dictionaries\n- Python has tuples\n- Python has sets\n- Python supports list comprehensions for concise list creation.\n- Warning: avoid using mutable objects as dictionary keys.\n- Python Getting Started.\n- Python virtual environments isolate project dependencies.\n\n## Origins and History\n\nHistorically, python was created by Guido van Rossum.. Python was first released in 1991.. Looking back, python was designed to emphasize code readability..\n\n## Getting Started\n\n1. To install Python, download the installer from python.org.\n\n## Rule\n\n- Python requires proper indentation for code blocks.\n- Python requires version 3.8 or higher for modern features.\n\n---\n\n## Sources\n\n[1] Python Programming Language (encyclopedic) — [source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language))\n[2] Python Official Documentation (official) — [source](https://docs.python.org/3/)\n[3] Python Getting Started (official) — [source](https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/)\n\n### See Also\n\n- Definition \"Python is a high-level, general-purpose ...\" generalizes to properties\n- Definition \"Python is consistently ranked among the ...\" generalizes to properties\n- \"Python requires proper indentation for c...\" requires \"Python Programming Language.\"\n- \"Python requires version 3.8 or higher fo...\" requires \"Python Programming Language.\"\n- Definition \"Python lists are mutable ordered sequenc...\" generalizes to properties",
